<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1306,466,585]" box="[151,1027,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[151,277,562,585]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,277,562,585]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Orthostolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: species 
<number box="[374,414,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="5.0">5–9</number>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sharp" box="[428,756,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. &amp; Scott, H. (1908) Coleoptera 3. In: D. Sharp (Ed.), Fauna Hawaiiensis: being the land-fauna of the Hawaiian Islands. Cambridge University Press, London, pp. 435 - 508." type="book chapter" year="1908">
Sharp &amp; Scott, 
<number box="[594,651,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1908.0">1908</number>
: 
<number box="[661,756,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="455.0" valueMax="456.0" valueMin="454.0">454–456</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) removed to 
<taxonomicName box="[898,1020,562,585]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Apetasimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[898,1020,562,585]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Apetasimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Diagnosis: Size medium to large, 4.5–7.7 mm L; 1.5–3.0 mm W. Size and color highly variable within species. Males usually dark brown to nearly black, dark markings weakly contrasting; females pale yellow to dark brown often with strongly contrasting dark markings similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[975,1173,714,740]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[975,1092,714,739]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Eupetinus</emphasis>
Sharp
</taxonomicName>
, most conspicuous on scutellum and abdomen. Pronotum with U-shaped area of anterior directed setae at anterior margin behind head. Antennal club compact, 
<number box="[509,523,794,820]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="9.0">9</number>
th antennomere transverse. Microsculpture of dorsum variable among species and within species, from granulate to fine lines, never obsolete and glabrous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Description: Eyes small, facets fine; temple short, acute, postgenae forming obtuse angle with occiput. Antennal grooves convergent, medial and lateral margins distinct. Antennal club elongate, antennomere nine transverse. Labrum with two pairs dorsal macrosetae; medial tooth broadly rounded; laterally sinuate to bisinuate, each side with two distinct patches of ventromarginal setae, a smaller patch of short setae adjacent to medial projection and a larger, longer patch before the lateral angle. Mandibles each with two apical teeth and three to six stout subapical teeth. Third labial palpomere subtransvers to weakly elongate, narrowed slightly distally.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Prothorax transverse. Lateral margins smoothly curved or recurved at posterior angle; smooth to weakly crenulate, marginal setae elongate, moderately dense for entire length. Pronotum with area of anterior directed setae behind at anterior margin behind head; remaining setae directed posteriorly. Prosternal process greatly expanded posterad of coxae, 
<number box="[498,542,1274,1300]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">
2– 
<date box="[529,542,1274,1300]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">3</date>
</number>
x minimum width between coxae; little recurved dorsad posterad of coxae; broadly curved at apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Elytra 
<date box="[281,310,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<number box="[281,295,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0">2</number>
x
</date>
as long as wide or less; lateral margin greater than 
<date box="[955,984,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<number box="[955,969,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0">2</number>
x
</date>
width of marginal bead, widest near humeral angle. Punctures of elytra coarse, forming distinct striae; striae 
<number box="[1028,1072,1394,1420]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="4.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="1.0">1–8</number>
nearly regular, 
<number box="[1266,1280,1394,1420]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="9.0">9</number>
and 
<number box="[1344,1373,1394,1420]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="10.0">10</number>
with punctures reduced, and increasingly more irregular toward elytral margin. Interstices of elytra slightly raised; wide with multiple confused rows of setae; interstices 
<number box="[783,798,1474,1500]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="6.0">6</number>
and 
<number box="[854,868,1474,1500]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.0">7</number>
dilated near middle, often extended distally and/ or proximally. Surface of elytra nearly even to distinctly uneven. Elytra exposing abdominal segments 
<number box="[1383,1431,1514,1540]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.6">7, 6</number>
, and part of 
<number box="[285,302,1554,1580]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="5.0">5</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" box="[198,1006,1594,1620]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Tarsomeres 
<number box="[340,385,1594,1620]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
with ventral lobes progressively dilated and bilobed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Male pygidium shallowly and broadly or narrowly emarginated to broadly rounded, angles rounded. Anal sclerite broadly rounded, truncate, or shallowly emarginate with angles rounded. Perisac length and form variable, from depressed and sub parallel to narrow proximally with distal 
<number box="[995,1005,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1016,1030,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="3.0">3</number>
– 
<number box="[1047,1057,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1068,1084,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="4.0">4</number>
expanded; flagellum reduced proximad of junction with sperm duct, flattened and truncate at proximal apex. Female pygidium broadly rounded; gonocoxae elongate. Basal ring of spermatheca weakly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,152,898]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis box="[198,496,1835,1860]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[198,411,1835,1860]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensu">
Orthostolus 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[346,411,1835,1860]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" sensu="stricto">sensu</taxonomicNameLabel>
</taxonomicName>
stricto
</emphasis>
is distributed on Kauai, Oahu, and Maui Nui and contains four described and five undescribed species. 
<emphasis box="[461,731,1875,1900]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[461,674,1875,1900]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensu">
Orthostolus 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[609,674,1875,1900]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" sensu="lato">sensu</taxonomicNameLabel>
</taxonomicName>
lato
</emphasis>
includes 
<number box="[849,878,1874,1900]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="14.0">14</number>
species from all of the high islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Sharp" pageId="21" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. &amp; Scott, H. (1908) Coleoptera 3. In: D. Sharp (Ed.), Fauna Hawaiiensis: being the land-fauna of the Hawaiian Islands. Cambridge University Press, London, pp. 435 - 508." type="book chapter" year="1908">
Sharp &amp; Scott 
<number box="[218,278,1914,1940]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1908.0">1908</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) though five described taxa are herein moved to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[965,1100,1915,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Apetasimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[965,1100,1915,1940]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Apetasimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The taxonomy of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Orthostolus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[192,203,1955,1980]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" sensu="stricto">s</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[211,222,1955,1980]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">s</emphasis>
. is in need of revision and examination of the male genitalia suggests there are two lineages with plesiomorphic, undescribed species on Kauai, each of which has colonized Oahu, Molokai, and Maui, with one lineage also present on Lanai. On East Maui three species can be collected sympatrically within a single stick, and dissection of male genitalia is required to distinguish them. Two of these species are present on West Maui. Two species were described from Oahu, 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[724,1019,232,258]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepos">
<emphasis box="[724,941,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus nepos</emphasis>
Sharp
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[1082,1432,232,258]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[1082,1331,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus robustus</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,397,272,297]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[151,397,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in both the Waianae and Koolau Mts. on Oahu and specimens from Lanai were included in the 
<emphasis box="[341,573,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fauna 
<taxonomicName box="[428,573,312,337]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hawaiiensis">Hawaiiensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
redescription (
<bibRefCitation author="Sharp" box="[755,897,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. (1878) On some Nitidulidae from the Hawaiian Islands. Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society London, 26, 127 - 140." type="journal article" year="1878">
Sharp 
<number box="[835,897,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1878.0">1878</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sharp" box="[912,1158,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. &amp; Scott, H. (1908) Coleoptera 3. In: D. Sharp (Ed.), Fauna Hawaiiensis: being the land-fauna of the Hawaiian Islands. Cambridge University Press, London, pp. 435 - 508." type="book chapter" year="1908">
Sharp &amp; Scott 
<number box="[1095,1158,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1908.0">1908</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The Lanai specimens previously considered 
<taxonomicName box="[422,561,352,378]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[422,443,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[461,561,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represent a distinct species; the male genitalia show it to be allied with 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[151,490,392,418]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="germanus">
<emphasis box="[151,414,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus germanus</emphasis>
Sharp
</taxonomicName>
of Molokai. 
<taxonomicName box="[649,864,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepos">
<emphasis box="[649,864,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus nepos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in the southern Koolau Mts. near Honolulu and is known from four male and one female specimen. Based on external morphology they appear to be allied with 
<taxonomicName box="[348,498,472,498]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="germanus">
<emphasis box="[348,369,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[383,498,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">germanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Lanai specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[834,970,472,498]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[834,855,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[870,970,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,152,898]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
All species of 
<emphasis box="[368,525,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName box="[368,507,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Orthostolus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[514,525,512,537]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" sensu="stricto">s</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[532,543,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">s</emphasis>
. are closely associated with decaying Hawaiian lobelioids in mesic and wet forests. Individuals can be found in actively decaying tissue of stems, droopy leaves, fruit, and flowers. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,289,592,617]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,289,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are all fully winged and can be collected occasionally on other plants in areas were their hosts occur. They are often very numerous with large numbers of both adults and larvae found together, and often share the substrate with species of 
<taxonomicName box="[580,697,672,697]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[580,697,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Eupetinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[844,1099,672,698]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="impressus">
<emphasis box="[844,862,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[881,997,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">impressus</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
. The species exhibit a high degree of intraspecific variability that overlaps that of other closely related species. They are variable in dorsal microsculpture, punctation, evenness of the surface, coloration, and the degree of sinuation at the hind angle of the pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,152,898]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName box="[198,336,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[198,336,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[490,653,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Cillaeopeplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[490,653,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Cillaeopeplus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ecologically and exhibits the same biogeographic pattern of speciation primarily through colonization from older to younger islands with little within-island differentiation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
